rect.title: A field of force refers to a region of space within which a body experiences a force without being in physical contact with any other body.

A FBD is a diagram showing all external forces acting ON an isolated body. This body is free because the diagram will show the body without its surroundings. This eliminates unnecessary information which might be given in a problem.
Draw object represented as a point. Draw all external forces pointing away from the object.
If the limit of proportionality is not exceeded, the extension is directly proportional to the force/ load applied.
Pressure is the force (Normal) per unit area acting on an object.
Upthrust is an upward force exerted by the fluid on a submerged or floating object due to the difference in pressure between the upper and lower surfaces of the object
Upthrust is equal in magnitude and opposite in direction to the weight of the fluid displaced by a submerged or floating object. This principle is known as Archimedes Principle.
When an object floats, the upthrust acting on it must be equal in magnitude and opposite in direction to the weight of the object since it is in vertical equilibrium.
The centre of gravity of an object is the point through which the entire weight of a body may be considered to act.
The moment of a force is defined as the product of the force and the perpendicular distance of its line of action from the pivot or axis of rotation.
The torque of a couple is defined as the product of one of the forces of the couple and the perpendicular distance between the lines of action of the forces.
1. The resultant force acting on it equals zero, (translational equilibrium) AND 2.The resultant moment about any point equals zero. (rotational equilibrium)

The Principle of Moments states that for a body to be in rotational equilibrium, the sum of all the anticlockwise moments about any point must be equal to the sum of all the clockwise moments about that same point.

If a body is acted upon by 3 forces (only) and remains in equilibrium 1.The lines of action of the forces must pass through a single (common) point 2. When a vector diagram of the 3 forces is drawn, the forces will form a closed triangle
